 among the first to reach the lake. The algae could &#39;suffocate&#39; the lake and make it very cold and even poisonous if certain species of algae bloom. I hope one/some of the answers discusses this."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/52bddd6ae812be4933dc7d26c41d96af?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":154,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/154/abe","reputation":446,"display_name":"Abe","accept_rate":67},"score":0,"post_id":10683,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f437d9a11deebd214089822c26197f35?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3553,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3553/james","reputation":4533,"display_name":"James","accept_rate":83},"edited":false,"creation_date":1384754848,"comment_id":17553,"body":"@goodgravy your scenario requires a healthy dose of nutrients"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f437d9a11deebd214089822c26197f35?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3553,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3553/james","reputation":4533,"display_name":"James","accept_rate":83},"score":0,"post_id":10683,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/52bddd6ae812be4933dc7d26c41d96af?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":154,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/154/abe","reputation":446,"display_name":"Abe","accept_rate":67},"edited":false,"creation_date":1384828787,"comment_id":17580,"body":"@Abe A very good point about nutrient rich water, especially considering we are starting from a blank slate. There many are trace elements in concrete, notably calcium. This is usually one of the limiting factor in algal growth. The other problem is nitrogen. This is where my theory has a weak link, yet I don&#39;t think we should dismiss that algae could thrive on whatever other micro organic matter found itself in the lake. Obviously if w