14564,"body":"You&#39;re absolutely right. Evolution is path-dependent. It can&#39;t progress toward features that would ultimately enhance fitness unless each step enhances fitness by itself."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/v5upF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3624,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3624/fileunderwater","reputation":10502,"display_name":"fileunderwater"},"score":0,"post_id":10882,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/06b0c88bb86cb532fc94663c6a566a0c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":827,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/827/octern","reputation":418,"display_name":"octern"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1382089075,"comment_id":14568,"body":"@octern This depends on population size. Founder effects or stochasticity in small populations can cause traits to go against fitness gradients, which could potentially bridge local fitness valleys."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/06b0c88bb86cb532fc94663c6a566a0c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":827,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/827/octern","reputation":418,"display_name":"octern"},"score":0,"post_id":10882,"edited":false,"creation_date":1382123828,"comment_id":14585,"body":"Perhaps it would have been more accurate for me to say that selection can&#39;t progress in that way. You&#39;re right that the overall process of evolution includes random events that prevent it from being a pure fitness maximization function."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/ZR6SM.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5005,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5005/hello-there-andy","reputation":1616,"display_name":"hello_there_andy","accept_rate":69},"score":0,"post_id":10882,"edited":false,"creation_date":1387246010,"comment_id":18378,"body":"very tempted to downvote this, please elaborate on what you mean 