ost<\/a> may be helpful.<\/p>\n","answer_id":13484,"question_id":13475,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/13475/how-cotranscription-events-affect-splicing","last_activity_date":1384430173,"creation_date":1384393764,"answer_count":1,"title":"How cotranscription events affect splicing?","body":"<p>I want to know how and how often does cootranscription takes place? Can transcription regulators influence splicing during cotranscription?<\/p>\n","question_id":13475,"tags":["transcription","splicing"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":92,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/f0PGT.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3615,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3615/biogirl","reputation":3923,"display_name":"biogirl","accept_rate":89},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/bb99b49a045d013d18badb900a5b8b81?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4908,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4908/andrew-bonnell","reputation":399,"display_name":"Andrew Bonnell"},"score":0,"post_id":13472,"edited":false,"creation_date":1384375865,"comment_id":17453,"body":"What class is this for?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/f0PGT.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3615,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3615/biogirl","reputation":3923,"display_name":"biogirl","accept_rate":89},"score":0,"post_id":13472,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/bb99b49a045d013d18badb900a5b8b81?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4908,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4908/andrew-bonnell","reputation":399,"display_name":"Andrew Bonnell"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1384447927,"comment_id":17475,"body":"for general bio class"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/VmtoK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1320,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1320/alan-boyd","reputation":17240,"display_name":"Alan Boyd"},"score":3,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1384414514,"creation_date":1384376428,"body":"<p>(B) is incorrect. I think the answer is (C) but to my mind those other two options are badly worded.<\/p>\n\n<p>Here is an explanation. <\/p>\n\n<p>The classic example of isozymes is the case of <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lactate_dehydrogenase\" rel=\"nofollow\">lactate dehydrogenase<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>As you will see if you visit the Wikipedia page the enzyme is a tetramer, and there are two subunit types, the <em>muscle<\/em> or M type and the <em>heart<\/em> or H type. Consequently there are 5 isozymes, ranging from M<sub>4<\/sub> to H<sub>4<\/sub> with all possible combinations in between. Different tissues express these two subunit types to different degrees and so are characterised by a different pattern of isozymes.<\/p>\n\n<p>The M type is encoded by the LDHA gene and the H type by the LDHB gene. I obtained the sequences of the two proteins and analysed them:<\/p>\n\n<p>LDHA: 332 amino acids; 36.7 kD; pI=8.45<\/p>\n\n<p>LDHB: 334 amino acids; 36.6 kD; pI=5.93<\/p>\n\n<p>You can see from this that the ability to separate these isozymes depends upon charge and not molecular weight. That big difference in pI (isoelectric point) means that at neutral pH the LDHA protein will carry a net positive charge while the LDHB protein will be negatively charged. Consequently each tetramer will have a unique overall charge. <a href=\"http://www.molvis.org/molvis/v11/a85/acosta-fig3.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">You can find some details and an image of an electrophoresis result here.<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>In general, protein electrophoresis is much more sensitive to charge differences than it is to molecular mass except in the special case of SDS-PAGE when the large amount of negatively-charged detergent that binds to the proteins masks their intrinsic charge differences. <\/p>\n\n<p>Another classic example of this is the ability to <a href=\"https://www.mun.ca/biology/scarr/Hemoglobin_Electrophoresis.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">separate haemoglobin S in sickle cell patients from haemoglobin A in normal blood<\/a>. In this case the only difference between the two molecules is a single Glu>Val substitution in two of the monomers in each tetramer. <\/p>\n","answer_id":13473,"question_id":13472,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1384414514}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/13472/electrophoretic-mobility-of-isozymes","last_activity_date":1384414514,"creation_date":1384372682,"answer_count":1,"title":"Electrophoretic mobility of isozymes","body":"<p>If isozymes are seperated using electrophoresis, which of the following will be the principle of separation ?<\/p>\n\n<p>A.charge density<\/p>\n\n<p>B.molecular weight<\/p>\n\n<p>C.polarity of molecule <\/p>\n\n<p>I think it should be B.<\/p>\n","question_id":13472,"tags":["molecular-biology","homework"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":13473,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":127,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/f0PGT.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3615,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3615/biogirl","reputation":3923,"display_name":"biogirl","accept_rate":89},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4f8a4da7480c620ebaa9ed7c31fb227b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4840,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4840/a-kennard","reputation":1429,"display_name":"A. Kennard"},"score":0,"post_id":13471,"edited":false,"creation_date":1384388020,"comment_id":17456,"body":"Wikipedia says the number of chloroplast DNA copies (nucleoids) drops from 100 to 15-20 as the chloroplast ages (<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chloroplast_DNA#Nucleoids\" rel=\"nofollow\">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chloroplast_DNA#Nucleoids<\/a>). No luck looking up membrane-bound ribo-/polysomes. I found lots on protein import into chloroplasts, but no export. My guess is that with many chloroplast genes migrating into the plant genome, protein flux is in rather than out (why would something the whole cell needs be made in just the chloroplast?). If you look at a list of chloroplast DNA genes, it&#39;s pretty self-contained; no proteins that would need to be exported."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":1,"post_id":13471,"edited":false,"creation_date":1384428498,"comment_id":17464,"body":"ribosomes are never membrane bound.. they are adsorbed on ER (in case of RER)"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889548c1e8387b3d381853dee5212cfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3632/shigeta","reputation":22684,"display_name":"shigeta","accept_rate":86},"score":3,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1384408564,"creation_date":1384408564,"body":"<p>The chloroplast, having multiple circular copies of its chromosome and its own tRNA and ribosome genes more resembles the bacterial systems it is descended from.  See @A.Kennard comment <\/p>\n\n<p>Polysomes being found in bacteria frequently are single mRNA to which are attached multiple ribosomes.  <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC335575/pdf/pnas00676-0293.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">This paper shows that chloroplast polysomes were observed in the mid 1960s by centrifugal sedimentation<\/a>.  <\/p>\n","answer_id":13477,"question_id":13471,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/13471/ribosomes-and-dna-in-chloroplast","last_activity_date":1384408564,"creation_date":1384371855,"answer_count":1,"title":"Ribosomes and DNA in chloroplast","body":"<p>Are there multiple copies of circular DNA and <strong>membrane bound<\/strong> ribosomes IN CHLOROPLAST ? \nAre polysomes found in them ?<\/p>\n","question_id":13471,"tags":["botany"],"score":0,"accepted_answer_id":13477,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":61,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/210cc4a4b2f281aaffe0b26521fe1ab8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1590,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1590/rg255","reputation":11513,"display_name":"rg255","accept_rate":66},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889548c1e8387b3d381853dee5212cfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3632/shigeta","reputation":22684,"display_name":"shigeta","accept_rate":86},"score":1,"post_id":13432,"edited":false,"creation_date":1384194136,"comment_id":17385,"body":"for one thing you have to add a stain to the gel to see it on the UV. ethidium bromide requires gloves and is toxic.  GelGreen/GelRed is expensive, but is a lot safer.  also remember to keep the mastermix frozen at -20C until use - aliquot it because you can&#39;t refreeze it more than ~6 times or so - it degrades."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/210cc4a4b2f281aaffe0b26521fe1ab8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1590,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1590/rg255","reputation":11513,"display_name":"rg255","accept_rate":66},"score":0,"post_id":13432,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889548c1e8387b3d381853dee5212cfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3632/shigeta","reputation":22684,"display_name":"shigeta","accept_rate":86},"edited":false,"creation_date":