t necessarily be 1, so the probability of an anenomefish species choosing <em>some<\/em> species of anenome would not be 1! <\/p>\n\n<p>NOTE: The reference to Manly 1993 was incorrect (you cited a 1995 paper); they actually cite a book: Manly B, McDonald L, Thomas D (1993) Resource selection by animals. <em>Statistical design and analysis for field studies<\/em>. Chapman and Hall, London. This would probably be the best place to look to get an exact answer to your question. I think that would be the best place to look first.<\/p>\n","answer_id":13405,"question_id":11394,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/11394/standardized-selection-ratio-ssr","last_activity_date":1384239412,"creation_date":1383983318,"answer_count":1,"title":"Standardized Selection Ratio (SSR)","body":"<p>In <a href=\"http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10641-010-9606-0#page-1\" rel=\"nofollow\">this<\/a> article the athors used the Standardized Selection Ratio (SSR) in order to infer what is the preferred host (anemone) of anemonefish.<\/p>\n\n<p>Here is a quotation coming from their methods:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>  The \u201cpreferred host\u201d of anemonefish was assessed calculating the \u201cStandardized\nSelection Ratio (SSR)\u201d (values between 0 and 1) (Manly et al. 1993). Manly\u2019s standardized\nselection ratio represents the probability that an individual will use a particular habitat\ntype, taking into account the different resource availability. For each anemonefish species (i) inhabiting an anemone species (j), SSR was calculated as:\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>$$SSR = \\frac{wi}{\\sum{}{wj}} $$<\/p>\n\n<p>where $wi = \\frac{oi}{pj}$<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>    `Oi` is the relative frequency of the anemonefish species i and `pj` the relative frequency\nof the anemone species j. Higher values of SSR indicate a strong preference for the\nselected resource. The Log- Likelihood statistic (χ2L) (Manly et al. 1993) was used to\ncheck the significance of the observed distribution under a null hypothesis of a random\nhost choice.\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://rads.stackoverflow.com/amzn/click/1402006772\" rel=\"nofollow\">Here<\/a> is the book they cite (Manly et al. 1993).<\/p>\n\n<p>Can you help me understanding basically what they did and how they calculated their <code>SSR<\/code> and p.values. If $wi = \\frac{oi}{pj}$ what does <code>wj<\/code> equals to?<\/p>\n","question_id":11394,"tags":["ecology","statistics","biostatistics","ecosystem","community-ecology"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":13405,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":208,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1384239412},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f8cff61025ca50307359795847257241?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":9,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9/greg-slodkowicz","reputation":852,"display_name":"Greg Slodkowicz"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/222b478bab6d59dc5de514a87dba88cd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":389,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/389/bobthejoe","reputation":4911,"display_name":"bobthejoe","accept_rate":53},"score":0,"post_id":951,"edited":false,"creation_date":1329935662,"comment_id":1370,"body":"What type of sequencing data do you have? Are we talking about RNA-seq or DNA?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/222b478bab6d59dc5de514a87dba88cd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":389,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/389/bobthejoe","reputation":4911,"display_name":"bobthejoe","accept_rate":53},"score":0,"post_id":951,"edited":false,"creation_date":1330079618,"comment_id":1412,"body":"I would reask this question on BioStar. They may have better ideas than we mere experimentalists."},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user4902"},"score":0,"post_id":951,"edited":false,"creation_date":13842