&quot; aspect ratio. My hypothesis is that the closer you look, the wider the effective aspect ratio is, and the further you look, the more circular it is. And if you cover one of your eyes, you&#39;ll probably get a circular FoV regardless of distance."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8921ce1c834fd3bcf773bd7305ac5b30?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1166,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1166/jello","reputation":911,"display_name":"jello"},"score":0,"post_id":5128,"edited":false,"creation_date":1352114383,"comment_id":7297,"body":"I have to agree with Kal, but mainly about #1. Essentially, the eyes are next to each other, and this allows for stereoscopic vision. If you cover one eye, your field of view is more or less circular (due to the retina and macula), but you&#39;ll lose depth perception. Plus, your eyelids slightly limit the amount you can see in the up-down directions."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/VmtoK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1320,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1320/alan-boyd","reputation":17240,"display_name":"Alan Boyd"},"score":0,"post_id":5128,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8921ce1c834fd3bcf773bd7305ac5b30?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1166,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1166/jello","reputation":911,"display_name":"jello"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1352142495,"comment_id":7306,"body":"@jello Surely the eyelids can&#39;t be having an effect as you describe because they don&#39;t normally cover any part of the pupils."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8921ce1c834fd3bcf773bd7305ac5b30?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1166,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1166/jello","reputation":911,"display_name":"jello"},"score":0,"post_id":5128,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://