6/user30561","reputation":109,"display_name":"user30561","accept_rate":0},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/11ecb2130d870caa97f33b9e9e658e19?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4109,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4109/resonating","reputation":3125,"display_name":"Resonating"},"score":0,"post_id":11246,"edited":false,"creation_date":1403709036,"comment_id":27457,"body":"Cancer is fundamentally a disease of genetics(it involves genes and genetic damage), but it&#39;s not a genetic disease in the way you might be thinking (strictly heritable). You cannot inherit cancer the way you inherit Huntington&#39;s. You can inherit an increased risk of cancer, though. Once you are born your genes are not fixed in stone forever. They can be changed with carcinogens or other processes."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/GqkqP.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4101,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4101/amory","reputation":7383,"display_name":"Amory"},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1383414636,"creation_date":1383405359,"body":"<p>Because cigarette smoke contains many <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carcinogen\" rel=\"nofollow\">carcinogens<\/a>.  Carcinogens can cause cancer by directly affecting the genome.  Wikipedia has a <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cigarette_smoke_carcinogens\" rel=\"nofollow\">list<\/a> of those present in cigarette smoke, which includes classics such as lead, benzene, and formaldehyde, not to mention radioactive polonium.<\/p>\n","answer_id":11248,"question_id":11246,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1383414636},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/956527c4c7be54d46ea6e8df78d97640?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4714,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4714/john-crout","reputation":31,"display_name":"John Crout"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8729233d525a654914051bf8c1234c78?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":115,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/115/nico","reputation":6011,"display_name":"nico","accept_rate":100},"score":0,"post_id":11258,"edited":false,"creation_date":1383491021,"comment_id":15107,"body":"The fact that not everyone who smokes develop cancer does not rule out that those carcinogens be (amongst) the causes of cancer in those people who do."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/VmtoK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1320,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1320/alan-boyd","reputation":17240,"display_name":"Alan Boyd"},"score":1,"post_id":11258,"edited":false,"creation_date":1383491891,"comment_id":15108,"body":"Just out of interest - how could it ever be shown that the carcinogens in cigarette smoke caused a specific case of cancer? My feeling is that this is impossible, and that the chain of potential causation from smoking&gt;carcinogens&gt;increased risk of lung cancer is as good as we can get."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1383490736,"creation_date":1383436640,"body":"<p>There are carcinogens in smoke but they've not been shown to be the cause of cancer in smokers.  Note that some smokers never develop cancer or heart disease; some have lived more than 100 years.<\/p>\n\n<p>Just because something is classified as a carcinogen doesn't mean it causes cancer in everyone and doesn't mean a given exposure to a particular carcinogen has any effect at all.  All smoking does is increase one's risk of developing cancer.  That it increases risk is not a fact but the association between smoking and cancer is significant, statistically.  (This means it meets certain mathematical criteria and is, therefore, not mere opinion).<\/p>\n\n<p>Chromosomal replication is not perfect and a healthy cell can replicate only a limited number of times.  Cancer is characterized (in part) by a loss of this control.    When DNA mutates in a way that results in the loss of this control an otherwise-healthy cell (now a mutation) results.  Smoking increases cell turnover and the increased turnover increases the likelihood this type of mutation will occur.<\/p>\n\n<p>You can think of skin cancers in the same way.  This is the reason an exposure resulting in a color change (sunburn, tanning including that from a tanning booth) increases the risk of skin cancer.<\/p>\n\n<p>Over a typical lifetime we develop a handful of cancerous tumors.  They're killed by our immune system.  Symptoms of malignant cancer develop when the immune system hasn't been effective.<\/p>\n","answer_id":11258,"question_id":11246,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1383490736}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/11246/how-does-smoking-an-environmental-factor-cause-cancer-fundamentally-a-genetic","last_activity_date":1383490736,"creation_date":1383404700,"answer_count":2,"title":"How does smoking, an environmental factor, cause cancer, fundamentally a genetic disease?","body":"<p>If cancer is fundamentally a genetic disease, how might an environmental factor such as smoking cause cancer?<\/p>\n","question_id":11246,"tags":["genetics","cancer","mutations"],"score":3,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":298,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1383405401},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/9ZslE.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1373,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1373/user1306322","reputation":578,"display_name":"user1306322","accept_rate":64},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/f0PGT.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3615,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3615/biogirl","reputation":3923,"display_name":"biogirl","accept_rate":89},"score":0,"post_id":11156,"edited"